	abstract = {The intermediate-mass star {\textless}i{\textgreater}β{\textless}i/{\textgreater} Pictoris is known to be surrounded by a structured edge-on debris disk within which a gas giant planet was discovered orbiting at 8−10 AU. The physical properties of {\textless}i{\textgreater}β{\textless}i/{\textgreater} Pic b were previously inferred from broad- and narrow-band 0.9−4.8 {\textless}i{\textgreater}μ{\textless}i/{\textgreater}m photometry. We used commissioning data of the Gemini Planet Imager (GPI) to obtain new astrometry and a low-resolution ({\textless}i{\textgreater}R{\textless}i/{\textgreater} {\textasciitilde} 35−39) {\textless}i{\textgreater}J{\textless}i/{\textgreater}-band (1.12−1.35 {\textless}i{\textgreater}μ{\textless}i/{\textgreater}m) spectrum of the planet. We find that the planet has passed the quadrature. We constrain its semi-major axis to ≤10 AU (90\% prob.) with a peak at 8.9{\textless}sup{\textgreater}+0.4{\textless}sup/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}-0.6{\textless}sub/{\textgreater} AU. The joint fit of the planet astrometry and the most recent radial velocity measurements of the star yields a planet dynamical mass lower than 20 {\textless}i{\textgreater}M{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}Jup{\textless}sub/{\textgreater} (≥96\% prob.). The extracted spectrum of {\textless}i{\textgreater}β{\textless}i/{\textgreater} Pic b is similar to those of young L1{\textless}sub{\textgreater}-1.5{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}{\textless}sup{\textgreater}+1{\textless}sup/{\textgreater} dwarfs. We used the spectral type estimate to revise the planet luminosity to log ({\textless}i{\textgreater}L{\textless}i/{\textgreater}/{\textless}i{\textgreater}L{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}⊙{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}) = −3.90 ± 0.07. The 0.9−4.8 {\textless}i{\textgreater}μ{\textless}i/{\textgreater}m photometry and spectrum are reproduced for {\textless}i{\textgreater}T{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}eff{\textless}sub/{\textgreater} = 1650 ± 150 K and a log {\textless}i{\textgreater}g{\textless}i/{\textgreater} ≤ 4.7 dex by 12 grids of PHOENIX-based and LESIA atmospheric models. For the most recent system age estimate (21 ± 4 Myr), the bolometric luminosity and the constraints on the dynamical mass of {\textless}i{\textgreater}β{\textless}i/{\textgreater} Pic b are only reproduced by warm- and hot-start tracks with initial entropies {\textless}i{\textgreater}S{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}{\textless}i{\textgreater}i{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}{\textgreater} 10.5 {\textless}i{\textgreater}k{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}B{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}/{\textless}i{\textgreater}baryon{\textless}i/{\textgreater}. These initial conditions may result from an inefficient accretion shock and/or a planetesimal density at formation higher than in the classical core-accretion model. Considering a younger age for the system or a conservative formation time for {\textless}i{\textgreater}β{\textless}i/{\textgreater} Pic b does not change these conclusions.},
