	abstract = {Sub-Neptunes (Rp{\textasciitilde}1.25-4 REarth) remain the most commonly detected 
exoplanets to date. However, it remains difficult for observations to
tell whether these intermediate-sized exoplanets have surfaces and where
their surfaces are located. Here we propose that the abundances of trace
species in the visible atmospheres of these sub-Neptunes can be used as
proxies for determining the existence of surfaces and approximate
surface conditions. As an example, we used a state-of-the-art
photochemical model to simulate the atmospheric evolution of K2-18b and
investigate its final steady-state composition with surfaces located at
different pressures levels (Psurf). We find the surface location has a
