photochemically-produced species can be recycled back to their favored
thermochemical-equilibrium forms and transported back to the upper
atmosphere. For an assumed H2-rich atmosphere for K2-18b, we identify
seven chemical species that are most sensitive to the existence of
surfaces: ammonia (NH3), methane (CH4), hydrogen cyanide (HCN),
acetylene (C2H2), ethane (C2H6), carbon monoxide (CO), and carbon
dioxide (CO2). The ratio between the observed and the no-surface
abundances of these species, can help distinguish the existence of a
shallow surface (Psurf {\textless} 10 bar), an intermediate surface (10 bar
