improvement in signal-to-noise ratio over the narrow-field HLC. We find
that, although the RV detection was marginal, the precursor RV data
enable the mass and orbit to be constrained with only 2 epochs of
starshade imaging. Including the HLC images in the analysis results in
improved measurements over RV + SS alone, with the greatest gains
resulting from images taken at epochs near maximum elongation. Combining
the two epochs of SS imaging with the RV + HLC data resulted in a factor
of {\textasciitilde}2 better orbit and mass determinations over RV + HLC alone. The
Roman CGI, combined with precursor RV data and later mission SS imaging,
form a powerful trifecta in detecting exoplanets and determining their
masses, albedos, and system configurations. While the Roman CGI will
break new scientific and technological ground with direct imaging of
giant exoplanets within {\textasciitilde}5 AU of V{\textasciitilde}5 and brighter stars, a Roman
Starshade Rendezvous mission would additionally enable the detection of
planets out to {\textasciitilde}8 AU in those systems.},
